{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Statutory Implications",
      "simpleDefinition": "The legal consequences, such as criminal records or fines, that occur when you break a law passed by Parliament.",
      "anchor": "Breaking the law leads to criminal court.",
      "misconception": "Believing that statutory breaches are only minor workplace issues rather than criminal offenses."
    },
    {
      "term": "Non-statutory Implications",
      "simpleDefinition": "The professional and safety consequences, like losing your job or damaging your career, that happen when you ignore industry guidance.",
      "anchor": "Ignoring guidance costs you your job and your reputation.",
      "misconception": "Thinking that because guidance isn't 'the law' directly, it can be safely ignored without consequence."
    },
    {
      "term": "Prohibition Notice",
      "simpleDefinition": "A legal order issued by the HSE that forces all work to stop immediately because the risk of injury is too high.",
      "anchor": "Stop work right now.",
      "misconception": "Thinking you are allowed to finish the current task before complying with the notice."
    },
    {
      "term": "Improvement Notice",
      "simpleDefinition": "A legal order that requires a specific safety violation to be fixed within a set amount of time.",
      "anchor": "Fix this safety issue by a set deadline.",
      "misconception": "Treating an improvement notice as a friendly suggestion rather than a legal requirement."
    },
    {
      "term": "Prosecution",
      "simpleDefinition": "The process of being taken to criminal court by the state for failing to follow statutory regulations.",
      "anchor": "Facing a judge for a criminal act.",
      "misconception": "Confusing criminal prosecution with a private disagreement or civil lawsuit."
    },
    {
      "term": "Reputational Damage",
      "simpleDefinition": "The loss of trust from clients and the industry, making it difficult to find future work.",
      "anchor": "Nobody hires an unsafe electrician.",
      "misconception": "Assuming that if you avoid a fine, your business or career hasn't been harmed."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Statutory means criminal court.",
    "Non-statutory means professional fallout.",
    "Prohibition means stop now.",
    "Improvement means fix it by the deadline.",
    "Non-compliance leads to loss of earnings."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Non-statutory guidance is optional.",
    "HSE notices are just advice.",
    "Statutory breaches only result in small fines.",
    "Dismissal is the same as prosecution."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "203-1b-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Statutory Implications",
      "objective": "Identify the legal consequences of breaching statutory regulations.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Statutory regulations are the law of the land. When you breach these, you are entering the criminal justice system. It is not a private matter between you and an employer; it is a matter of the state versus the individual or company. The most direct consequence is prosecution, which can lead to a criminal record, substantial fines, or even imprisonment. These aren't just minor penalties—they are designed to punish and deter unsafe practices.",
        "The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) acts as the enforcement body. They can issue a Prohibition Notice, which legally forces you to stop work immediately because the risk of serious injury is too high. Alternatively, they might issue an Improvement Notice. This is a legal order requiring you to fix a specific safety issue within a set timeframe. Failing to comply with these notices is a criminal offense in itself. Statutory implications are about legal accountability and the potential loss of your liberty or business."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the legal and criminal outcomes that come from breaking the law, such as court action and HSE notices."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-1b-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Non-statutory Implications",
      "objective": "Identify the professional and safety consequences of failing to follow non-statutory guidance.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Non-statutory regulations, such as BS 7671 or the On-Site Guide, provide the technical standards for safe electrical work. While they aren't 'the law' in the same way an Act of Parliament is, the implications of ignoring them are devastating. Professionally, failing to follow industry guidance often leads to dismissal. Employers cannot risk the liability of an electrician who ignores standard safety procedures.",
        "Beyond losing your current job, you face significant reputational damage. In the electrical trade, your reputation is your most valuable asset; once it is tarnished by poor practice, you will see a sharp loss of clients and future earnings. Most critically, these regulations exist to prevent injury or death. If an installation you worked on causes a fire or an electric shock because you ignored the guidance, you will be held civilly liable. In a court of law, following non-statutory guidance is often the only way to prove you weren't negligent. Ignoring these standards effectively ends your career and puts lives at risk."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about the professional fallout, such as losing your job or your reputation, and the physical risks like injury."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Statutory Implications",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the legal term for the process of being taken to criminal court for failing to follow statutory regulations?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Prosecution",
            "Criminal prosecution",
            "Being prosecuted"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which specific legal order issued by the HSE forces all work to stop immediately due to high risk?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Prohibition Notice",
            "A Prohibition Notice",
            "Prohibition"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What is the name of the legal order that requires a safety violation to be fixed within a specific timeframe?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Improvement Notice",
            "An Improvement Notice",
            "Improvement"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why does a breach of statutory regulations involve the state and the criminal justice system rather than just being a private workplace matter?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "Statutory regulations are laws passed by Parliament",
        "Breaches are considered criminal offenses against the state",
        "The HSE enforces these laws on behalf of the public",
        "Penalties like imprisonment and criminal records are handled by courts"
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on the legal and criminal outcomes that come from breaking the law, such as court action and HSE notices."
    },
    {
      "title": "Non-statutory Implications",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What is the professional consequence when an employer terminates an electrician's employment for ignoring safety procedures?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Dismissal",
            "Being dismissed",
            "Getting sacked"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What term describes the loss of trust from clients that makes it difficult for an electrician to find future work?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Reputational damage",
            "Damage to reputation",
            "Loss of reputation"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Besides professional and financial loss, what is the most critical physical implication of ignoring non-statutory safety guidance?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Injury or death",
            "Physical injury",
            "Death"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "How does following non-statutory guidance like BS 7671 provide a legal defense for an electrician if an installation is questioned in court?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "It proves the electrician was not negligent",
        "It demonstrates that industry-standard safety procedures were followed",
        "It shows the work met the required technical standards",
        "It provides evidence of professional competence during a civil liability claim"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about the professional fallout, such as losing your job or your reputation, and the physical risks like injury."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "guidedPractice": {
    "title": "Guided Practice",
    "objective": "Categorize specific outcomes into statutory and non-statutory implications based on a workplace scenario.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Scenario: An electrician, Sarah, fails to carry out mandatory insulation resistance testing on a new circuit, ignoring both the requirements of BS 7671 and the Electricity at Work Regulations (EAWR). During a site audit, the breach is discovered.",
      "Step 1: Identify the Statutory Implication. Because Sarah breached the EAWR (the law), the HSE can take legal action. This results in a criminal Prosecution or a heavy Fine.",
      "Step 2: Identify the Non-statutory Implication. Because Sarah ignored the professional standards in BS 7671, her employer loses trust in her work. This leads to her Dismissal and causes the firm Reputational Damage."
    ],
    "questionText": "In the scenario provided, Sarah's failure to test the circuit results in both legal and professional fallout. Identify one specific statutory implication and one specific non-statutory implication she faces.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Statutory: Prosecution, Fines, or Imprisonment",
      "Non-statutory: Dismissal, Reputational damage, or Loss of earnings"
    ],
    "hint": "Statutory implications are legal penalties like prosecution; non-statutory implications are professional consequences like dismissal."
  },
  "practice": {
    "title": "Practice",
    "objective": "Evaluate a scenario of non-compliance to correctly identify the specific likely implications from the regulatory range.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Scenario: A small electrical firm is found to be using faulty power tools that do not meet PUWER safety standards. An HSE inspector determines the tools are not an immediate danger but must be repaired or replaced within 14 days to meet the law. Meanwhile, the firm's main client hears about the safety breach and cancels their ongoing maintenance contract."
    ],
    "questionText": "Based on the scenario, state the specific statutory notice issued by the HSE to fix the tools, and identify the specific non-statutory implication resulting from the client's reaction.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Statutory: Improvement Notice",
      "Non-statutory: Loss of clients or Loss of earnings"
    ],
    "hint": "The HSE issues a notice to 'improve' safety within a timeframe. When a client cancels a contract, it is a professional loss of business."
  }
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close",
    "objective": "Synthesize the impact of a major site incident by identifying both the statutory legal penalties and the non-statutory professional fallout.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In the electrical industry, a single safety failure triggers two distinct chains of consequences. First, the statutory chain involves the government (HSE) enforcing the law through notices and the courts. Second, the non-statutory chain involves the industry and clients reacting to your lack of professional standards.",
      "To be a competent electrician, you must understand that while a fine might hurt your bank account today, a loss of reputation or a prohibition notice can end your career entirely. You are accountable to both the law and the professional community."
    ],
    "questionText": "Scenario: An electrician is found working on a live, exposed busbar system without any safety barriers or justification, violating the Electricity at Work Regulations and BS 7671. The HSE inspector issues a legal order to stop all work on that site immediately. Following this, the electrician is removed from the project and finds that other local firms are now refusing to hire them. \n\nIdentify the specific statutory notice issued by the HSE in this scenario, and state the specific non-statutory implication that is preventing the electrician from finding new work.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Statutory: Prohibition Notice",
      "Non-statutory: Reputational damage (or Loss of earnings/clients)"
    ],
    "hint": "Statutory notices that halt work immediately have a specific name. Professional consequences that stop you from getting future work relate to how others perceive your reliability."
  }
}

